{"title_page": "Ardstinchar Castle", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox military installation\n| name = Ardstinchar Castle\n| ensign = \n| native_name = \n| partof = <!-- for elements within a larger site -->\n| location = \n| nearest_town = <!-- used in military test site infobox -->\n| country = [[United Kingdom]]\n| image = Ardstinchar Castle, Ballantrae - geograph.org.uk - 692808.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Remains of Ardstinchar Castle\n| image2 = <!--secondary image, major command emblems for airfields -->\n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = \n| type = \n| coordinates = {{coord|55.098|-5.00028|type:Castle|display=inline}}\n| image_map =\n| image_mapsize = \n| image_map_alt = \n| image_map_caption = \n| pushpin_map = \n| pushpin_mapsize = \n| pushpin_map_alt = \n| pushpin_map_caption = \n| pushpin_relief = \n| pushpin_image = \n| pushpin_label = \n| pushpin_label_position = \n| pushpin_mark = \n| pushpin_marksize = \n| ownership = <!-- government department such as the MoD or the United States DoD -->\n| operator = <!-- where different from ownership such as the RAF or the USAF -->\n| controlledby = <!-- such as RAF Bomber Command or the Eighth Air Force -->\n| open_to_public = <!-- for out of use sites/sites with museums etc -->\n| site_other_label = <!-- for renaming \"Other facilities\" in infobox -->\n| site_other = <!-- for other sorts of facilities - radar types etc -->  \n| site_area = <!-- area of site m2, km2 square mile etc -->\n| code = <!--facility/installation code, applies to US -->\n| built = mid-15th century\n| used = <!--{{End date|1946}} -->\n| builder = [[Hugh Kennedy of Ardstinchar]]\n| materials = Stone\n| height = <!-- height of tallest part, not above sea level --> 15 metres\n| fate = <!--changed from demolished parameter--> demolished\n| condition = \n| battles = \n| events = \n| current_commander = <!-- current commander -->\n| past_commanders = <!-- past notable commander(s) -->\n| garrison = <!-- such as the 25th Bombardment Group -->\n| occupants = <!-- squadrons only -->\n| website = \n| footnotes = <!-- catchall in case it's needed to preserve something in infobox that doesn't work in new code -->\n}}\n'''Ardstinchar Castle''' is a late medieval castle in the west coast of [[Ayrshire]] at the mouth of the [[River Stinchar]]. It was built by [[Hugh Kennedy of Ardstinchar]] in the mid-15th century. In the 1770s, the castle was demolished and the stone was used to build a bridge over the River Stinchar. Only remnants of the castle [[keep]] remain to this day.<ref name=\"ay\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SGCfYDaNq94C&printsec=frontcover|title=The Ayrshire and Arran Coastal Paths|author= Keith Fergus}}</ref><ref name=\"ar\">{{cite web|url=http://canmore.org.uk/site/60946/ardstinchar-castle|title=Ardstinchar Castle|work=canmore.org}}</ref> The site is a [[scheduled monument]].<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=SM311 |desc=Ardstinchar Castle|access-date=19 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Ardstinchar Castle and bridge, Ballantrae, Scotland-LCCN2001703588.jpg|thumb|Ardstinchar Castle and bridge]]\nArdstinchar Castle was built by Hugh Kennedy of Ardstinchar, originally a Dominican friar who left his monastery to travel to France, where he took part in the [[Hundred Years' War]] as a mercenary and led troops for [[Joan of Arc]] at the [[Siege of Orl\u00e9ans]] (1428\u20131429).<ref name=\"ay\" /><ref name=\"ar\" /> He probably inherited the land from his brother, Alexander, who died without issue, and held it by 1429. With another brother, Thomas, he combined estates to form the Barony of Ardstinchar, but retained a [[Liferent (Scots law)|liferent]] on his own land until his death in 1454. His descendants lived in Ardstinchar Castle for more than a century.<ref name=\"mary\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mariestuartsociety.org/articles-ardstinchar.php|title=Ardstinchar Castle \u2013 The Marian Connection|work=mariestuartsociety.org|access-date=2015-10-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151122191029/http://www.mariestuartsociety.org/articles-ardstinchar.php|archive-date=2015-11-22|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Mary, Queen of Scots]] visited the castle in 1563. She is likely to have strolled and admired the view on the half turret walkway which still remains today.<ref name=\"mary\"/>\n\nA long-standing family feud between the Cassillis and the [[Kennedy Clan]], which started in Hugh Kennedy's era, ended in 1601 with the murder of the last [[Gilbert Kennedy of Bargany and Ardstinchar|baron of Bargany and Ardstinchar]].<ref name=\"mary\" /> [[Jean Stewart, Lady Bargany|Jean Stewart]], the widow of Bargany, who had been a lady in waiting to [[Anne of Denmark]], stayed on at Ardstinchar and resisted an attempt to evict her in 1603. She died in 1605.<ref>''Register of the Privy Council'', vol. 6 (Edinburgh, 1884), p. 579, 790.</ref> The family fortunes were lost, and the estate was bought by Sir John Hamilton of Letterick, son of [[John Hamilton, 1st Marquess of Hamilton|the 1st Marquis of Hamilton]].<ref name=\"mary\" /> By 1770, the castle had fallen into disrepair and was quarried to provide stone for the construction of a three-arch bridge over the [[River Stinchar]], as well as several houses and an inn in Ballantrae, now the King's Arms Hotel.<ref name=\"ay\" /><ref name=\"mary\" />\n\n==Architecture==\nLittle remains of the castle today apart from the ruins of the keep on a rocky hill. The original castle was wedge-shaped and had three square towers connected by battlement walls. The gatehouse was on the north side, and the keep was in the southeast part of the courtyard with a long hall house alongside.<ref name=\"mary\" />\n\nThe remains of the castle are situated on the [[outcrop|rock outcrop]] summit near the river. The main tower is {{Convert|8.7|x|6|m}} and walls are {{Convert|1.1|m}} thick. From the ground, it has a height of {{Convert|15|m}}. The remains of the other towers are too small to measure. The courtyard wall varies from {{Convert|1|to|1.6|m}} wide. A rock-cut trench, {{Convert|8|m}} wide and {{Convert|1.5|m}} deep, lies outside the north-east courtyard wall, and there is another shallow trench in the west.<ref name=\"ar\" />\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Ardstinchar Castle}}\n* [[Balthayock Castle]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FhNJ7stgpj0 Video footage of Ardstinchar Castle]\n\n{{Castles in South Ayrshire}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Listed castles in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Renaissance architecture in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Castles in South Ayrshire]]\n[[Category:Scheduled Ancient Monuments in South Ayrshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox military installation\n| name = Ardstinchar Castle\n| ensign = \n| native_name = \n| partof = <!-- for elements within a larger site -->\n| location = \n| nearest_town = <!-- used in military test site infobox -->\n| country = [[United Kingdom]]\n| image = Ardstinchar Castle, Ballantrae - geograph.org.uk - 692808.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Remains of Ardstinchar Castle\n| image2 = <!--secondary image, major command emblems for airfields -->\n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = \n| type = \n| coordinates = {{coord|55.098|-5.00028|type:Castle|display=inline}}\n| image_map =\n| image_mapsize = \n| image_map_alt = \n| image_map_caption = \n| pushpin_map = \n| pushpin_mapsize = \n| pushpin_map_alt = \n| pushpin_map_caption = \n| pushpin_relief = \n| pushpin_image = \n| pushpin_label = \n| pushpin_label_position = \n| pushpin_mark = \n| pushpin_marksize = \n| ownership = <!-- government department such as the MoD or the United States DoD -->\n| operator = <!-- where different from ownership such as the RAF or the USAF -->\n| controlledby = <!-- such as RAF Bomber Command or the Eighth Air Force -->\n| open_to_public = <!-- for out of use sites/sites with museums etc -->\n| site_other_label = <!-- for renaming \"Other facilities\" in infobox -->\n| site_other = <!-- for other sorts of facilities - radar types etc -->  \n| site_area = <!-- area of site m2, km2 square mile etc -->\n| code = <!--facility/installation code, applies to US -->\n| built = mid-15th century\n| used = <!--{{End date|1946}} -->\n| builder = [[Hugh Kennedy of Ardstinchar]]\n| materials = Stone\n| height = <!-- height of tallest part, not above sea level --> 15 metres\n| fate = <!--changed from demolished parameter--> demolished\n| condition = \n| battles = \n| events = \n| current_commander = <!-- current commander -->\n| past_commanders = <!-- past notable commander(s) -->\n| garrison = <!-- such as the 25th Bombardment Group -->\n| occupants = <!-- squadrons only -->\n| website = \n| footnotes = <!-- catchall in case it's needed to preserve something in infobox that doesn't work in new code -->\n}}\n'''Ardstinchar Castle''' is a late medieval castle in the west coast of [[Ayrshire]] at the mouth of the [[River Stinchar]]. It was built by [[Hugh Kennedy of Ardstinchar]] in the mid-15th century. In the 1770s, the castle was demolished and the stone was used to build a bridge over the River Stinchar. Only remnants of the castle [[keep]] remain to this day.<ref name=\"ay\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SGCfYDaNq94C&printsec=frontcover|title=The Ayrshire and Arran Coastal Paths|author= Keith Fergus}}</ref><ref name=\"ar\">{{cite web|url=http://canmore.org.uk/site/60946/ardstinchar-castle|title=Ardstinchar Castle|work=canmore.org}}</ref> The site is a [[scheduled monument]].<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=SM311 |desc=Ardstinchar Castle|access-date=19 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Ardstinchar Castle and bridge, Ballantrae, Scotland-LCCN2001703588.jpg|thumb|Ardstinchar Castle and bridge]]\nArdstinchar Castle was built by Hugh Kennedy of Ardstinchar, originally a Dominican friar who left his monastery to travel to France, where he took part in the [[Hundred Years' War]] as a mercenary and led troops for [[Joan of Arc]] at the [[Siege of Orl\u00e9ans]] (1428\u20131429).<ref name=\"ay\" /><ref name=\"ar\" /> He probably inherited the land from his brother, Alexander, who died without issue, and held it by 1429. With another brother, Thomas, he combined estates to form the Barony of Ardstinchar, but retained a [[Liferent (Scots law)|liferent]] on his own land until his death in 1454. His descendants lived in Ardstinchar Castle for more than a century.<ref name=\"mary\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mariestuartsociety.org/articles-ardstinchar.php|title=Ardstinchar Castle \u2013 The Marian Connection|work=mariestuartsociety.org|access-date=2015-10-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151122191029/http://www.mariestuartsociety.org/articles-ardstinchar.php|archive-date=2015-11-22|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Mary, Queen of Scots]] visited the castle in 1563. She is likely to have strolled and admired the view on the half turret walkway which still remains today.<ref name=\"mary\"/>\n\nA long-standing family feud between the Cassillis and the [[Kennedy Clan]], which started in Hugh Kennedy's era, ended in 1601 with the murder of the last [[Gilbert Kennedy of Bargany and Ardstinchar|baron of Bargany and Ardstinchar]].<ref name=\"mary\" /> Jean Stewart, the widow of Bargany, who had been a lady in waiting to [[Anne of Denmark]], stayed on at Ardstinchar and resisted an attempt to evict her in 1603. She died in 1605.<ref>''Register of the Privy Council'', vol. 6 (Edinburgh, 1884), p. 579, 790.</ref> The family fortunes were lost, and the estate was bought by Sir John Hamilton of Letterick, son of [[John Hamilton, 1st Marquess of Hamilton|the 1st Marquis of Hamilton]].<ref name=\"mary\" /> By 1770, the castle had fallen into disrepair and was quarried to provide stone for the construction of a three-arch bridge over the [[River Stinchar]], as well as several houses and an inn in Ballantrae, now the King's Arms Hotel.<ref name=\"ay\" /><ref name=\"mary\" />\n\n==Architecture==\nLittle remains of the castle today apart from the ruins of the keep on a rocky hill. The original castle was wedge-shaped and had three square towers connected by battlement walls. The gatehouse was on the north side, and the keep was in the southeast part of the courtyard with a long hall house alongside.<ref name=\"mary\" />\n\nThe remains of the castle are situated on the [[outcrop|rock outcrop]] summit near the river. The main tower is {{Convert|8.7|x|6|m}} and walls are {{Convert|1.1|m}} thick. From the ground, it has a height of {{Convert|15|m}}. The remains of the other towers are too small to measure. The courtyard wall varies from {{Convert|1|to|1.6|m}} wide. A rock-cut trench, {{Convert|8|m}} wide and {{Convert|1.5|m}} deep, lies outside the north-east courtyard wall, and there is another shallow trench in the west.<ref name=\"ar\" />\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Ardstinchar Castle}}\n* [[Balthayock Castle]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FhNJ7stgpj0 Video footage of Ardstinchar Castle]\n\n{{Castles in South Ayrshire}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Listed castles in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Renaissance architecture in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Castles in South Ayrshire]]\n[[Category:Scheduled Ancient Monuments in South Ayrshire]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ardstinchar_Castle"}
